('b01095e0-bd4b-11e8-ba1a-6d1ecea8d8c6', 'Status of Dominant Small Pelagic in Hinatuan Passage Caraga Region, Philippines', '\"[{\\\"id\\\":0,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Joyce M. Baclayo\\\"},{\\\"id\\\":1,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Romeo C. Deligero\\\"},{\\\"id\\\":2,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Laila M. Holoyohoy\\\"},{\\\"id\\\":3,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Eunice C. Bognot\\\"}]\"', '<h3>Abstract</h3><br><div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><i>Rastrelliger kanagurta, Selar crumneophthalmus, Decapterus russelli and Amblygaster sirm</i>&nbsp;were the dominant small pelagic fishes in Hinatuan Passage contributing 32% of the total production in the area. This paper presents the status of these four dominant small pelagic fishes as to their abundance, seasonality, length frequency distribution and population parameters relevant to the management and sustainability of the fishery resources in the area. Results show that commercial Danish seine, Ring nets, Bagnets and municipal multiple hook and lines and drift gillnets, were the main fishing gears exploiting these four small pelagic fishes. It was show further in the analysis of fish samples that these gears caught an average of 77% immature fish which did not even reach its length at first maturity, though the growth rate (K) and length infinity (L) vary by species. The present level of exploitation rates ranged from 0.4-0.84 which is an indication of biological overfishing.</div>', 'Small pelagic species catch per unit effort,population parameters', 2, 12, 122, '2004-01-01', '2013-12-01', 'BFAR', '20000000', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'img20180921_08100664.pdf', 164839, 1, 0, 'f85e2470-b564-11e8-91a2-d1382041221b', '2018-09-20 19:09:00', '2018-09-20 19:09:00'),
